Abstract
Large Language Model-based multi-agent systems have shown
promise in automating software development tasks. However, most
vibe code systems focus on completing small tasks and incremental
code changes, leaving persistent, continuous software development
largely unexplored. We present TheBotCompany1 , an open-source
orchestration framework for continuous multi-agent software development. TheBotCompany introduces three key innovations:
(1) a three-phase state machine (Strategy → Execution → Verification) for milestone-driven development, (2) self-organizing
agent teams where manager agents dynamically hire, assign, and
fire worker agents based on project needs, and (3) asynchronous
human oversight. We evaluate TheBotCompany on real-world
software projects over multiple days of continuous development,
measuring team adaptation patterns, milestone completion rates,
cost efficiency, and code quality. Our results demonstrate that the
self-organizing approach enables effective long-term software development with measurable progress, while the verification phase
catches defects that would otherwise persist.
