The cycle waste ratio (failed cycles / total) was near zero for
Projects A, B, and D. In Project C, 27 fix-round milestones represent
acknowledged rework cycles; if these are classified as waste, the
waste ratio is 27/392 = 6.9%—a modest overhead given the iterative
nature of pixel-fidelity optimization. In projdevbench problem 4,
approximately 120 late cycles targeted an unresolvable bug, yielding
an estimated waste ratio of 31%.
Finding (RQ5): Failure modes are domain-specific; orchestrationlevel failures (timeouts, tooling) are rare and recover within one cycle.
Self-aware termination—explicit documentation of irreducible limitations—prevents runaway cost in both the long-running settings.

4.4

Threats to Validity

Internal Validity. The primary internal threat is non-determinism
of LLMs: all agent invocations use non-zero temperature, so rerunning any project would produce different milestone decompositions,
different code artifacts, and potentially different quality outcomes.
We report single-run results, which precludes variance estimation.
A second internal threat is researcher involvement in project configuration: initial project briefs and acceptance criteria were authored
by the research team, and while Athena autonomously refines milestones, the starting specification influences the development trajectory. We mitigate this by reporting outcomes only (not handcrafted
milestones) and by using objective quality metrics (benchmark
correctness, test pass rates, pixel similarity) wherever possible.
External Validity. Four long-running projects may not represent
the distribution of real-world software tasks. Our selection skews
toward system projects (simulator, database engine, compiler, interpreter) with deterministic correctness oracles–a favorable setting
for verification-driven development. Projects involving ambiguous
requirements are not evaluated. The ProjDevBench comparison
is externally scored by the benchmark authors’ OJ system, which
partially mitigates selection bias for the RQ2 results. Finally, all
experiments use Claude-family models; it is unknown whether the
multi-agent coordination benefit holds with other LLM backends.

Construct Validity. Several proxies may not capture the intended
constructs. LOC and test count are imperfect surrogates for software quality; a project can accumulate LOC while making no functional progress. We supplement LOC with domain-specific metrics
(PolyBench accuracy, TPC-H query coverage, pixel similarity, OJ
execution scores) to reduce dependence on any single proxy. The
verification agent (Apollo) itself relies on LLM judgment for qualitative assessments, introducing the possibility that Apollo incorrectly
passes or rejects a milestone; we partially address this by anchoring
acceptance criteria to executable tests rather than Apollo’s prose
evaluation wherever possible. Finally, cost comparisons between
TheBotCompany and single-agent baselines in the long-running
track are not available, as running multi-day sessions with Claude
Code under identical conditions and budgets was not feasible.

5

Discussion

Sequential Phase Separation vs. Parallel Competition. Although we compared against with Claude Code’s single-agent mode,
the agent teams mode [4], which coordinates multiple Claude Code
instances under a single team lead, represents an emerging alternative paradigm. We did not include a direct comparison because the
feature remains experimental and is not publicly available through
standard usage, and results would be difficult to reproduce and
unfair to both systems. Conceptually, however, the architectures
differ in a fundamental way. Claude Code’s teams favor parallel,
competitive coordination—agents attempt the same task and the
lead selects the best result—whereas TheBotCompany enforces
sequential phase separation: planning, implementation, and verification are isolated so that each stage cannot be contaminated by
the concerns of another. Independent verification is only meaningful when the verifier has no stake in the implementation, a
principle that parallels the self-critique loops shown to improve
agent quality in Reflexion [44]. We hypothesize that this separation
explains the performance pattern observed in RQ2: on compact
problems amenable to a single session, single execution is sufficient; on high-difficulty problems requiring iterative refinement,
sequential phase separation with persistent verification feedback
provides a structural advantage. As such, rigorous empirical validation of this hypothesis, ideally on a shared benchmark with both
systems, is an important direction for future work.
When does multi-agent coordination justify its cost? Our
results suggest a practical crossover point. On ProjDevBench problems where the solution space is large and requires iterative exploration (P3, P17), TheBotCompany outperforms single-agent
baselines despite consuming 1.65× more output tokens per attempt.
On problems admitting compact, single-session solutions (P16),
the multi-agent overhead reduces both score and cost-efficiency.
For practitioners, this implies that multi-agent orchestration is
best suited to projects where (1) the implementation cannot be
completed in a single session, (2) quality criteria are continuous
or iterative rather than binary, and (3) the cost of undetected regressions justifies an independent verification phase. When these
conditions do not hold, a single-agent tool is likely more efficient.
Human-in-the-loop Oversight Granularity. TheBotCompany was designed for largely unattended operation, with human
steering channeled through asynchronous issue filing. In practice,

Self-Organizing Multi-Agent Systems for Continuous Software Development

adding live agent output streaming to the dashboard created an
implicit expectation of finer-grained control. For example, users
who could watch a worker diverge naturally wanted to correct it
mid-cycle. This reflects a tension in mixed-initiative systems [23]:
exposing system internals raises awareness of errors but shifts the
perceived locus of control, increasing felt demand for intervention.
The appropriate granularity of oversight depends on user expertise and task stakes [2]—a domain expert debugging a numerical
simulator has actionable knowledge that a generalist user does not.
Our experience suggests a tiered model: coarse-grained issue filing
for users who prefer autonomy; mid-grained pause/bootstrap for
correcting runaway cycles; and potential fine-grained interruption
for experts who can productively redirect an in-progress agent.
However, how to expose these tiers without overburdening the
agent communication infrastructure deserves more future work.

6

Conclusion

We presented TheBotCompany, an open-source framework for
continuous multi-agent software development built around three
innovations: a repeating Strategy → Execution → Verification
lifecycle, self-organizing worker teams that managers compose per
milestone, and budget-aware scheduling for unattended operation.
Evaluation across four real-world projects and five problems yields
three findings. First, the verification phase adds corrective value
when acceptance criteria are continuous or iterative, but acts as
confirmatory overhead when deterministic oracles are available,
suggesting that verification cost should be calibrated to specification
clarity. Second, self-organizing teams concentrate cost on implementation work, with orchestration overhead remaining stable as
projects grow. Third, in a single-run comparison, TheBotCompany
achieved higher scores than the same-model single-agent baselines
on high-difficulty problems requiring iterative refinement, while
single-agent execution was more efficient on problems amenable
to single-session solutions. Collectively, our results suggest that
structural choices—phase separation, persistent state, and decoupled verification—are important complements to model capability
for long-horizon software development.

